    <section class="orientation">
        <h2>Importance of Orientation</h2>
        <p>Verbal language uses several letters to compose endless combinations. The way sign languages approach this is
            similar, using the hand direction
            and fingers to represent the particular word. Just like the words brood and broad are only a one letter
            difference, signs do the same, the
            difference between the letter A and S is the position of the thumb in the sign..</p>
    </section>

    <section class="hand-direction">
        <h2>Hand Direction</h2>
        <p>The direction of the hand is of great importance, not only because it can change the word entirely, it also
            is crucial in the readability of your
            signs. Think of a limp wrist symbolizing a slurred word, it can be harder to read and understand if your
            sign isn't properly displayed. When
            displaying a sign, your hand should be steady with your palm typically facing your listener and each sign
            should be completed and pronounced before
            starting the next</p>
    </section>

    <section class="finger-identification">
